### Console Output

TypeScript uses the same console methods as JavaScript for output.

### console.log()

```typescript
console.log("Hello, World!");
console.log(42);
console.log(true);
```

### console.table()

Display tabular data:

```typescript
const users = [
  { name: "Alice", age: 30 },
  { name: "Bob", age: 25 }
];
console.table(users);
```

### Template Literals

Use backticks for string interpolation:

```typescript
let name: string = "TypeScript";
console.log(`Welcome to ${name}`);
```

### Format Specifiers

| Specifier | Description |
|-----------|------------|
| %s | String |
| %d | Number (integer) |
| %i | Integer |
| %f | Float |
| %o | Object |
| %c | CSS style |

```typescript
console.log("Name: %s, Age: %d", "Alice", 30);
```

### Grouping and Styling

```typescript
console.group("User Details");
console.log("Name: Alice");
console.log("Age: 30");
console.groupEnd();

console.log("%cStyled text", "color: blue; font-size: 20px");
```

> **Key Point:** console methods work identically in TypeScript and JavaScript.

codeExample:
// Basic output
console.log("Basic log message");

// Template literals
const app: string = "TypeScript";
const version: number = 5.6;
console.log(`${app} version ${version}`);

// Table output
console.table([
  { lang: "TypeScript", type: "Statically typed" },
  { lang: "JavaScript", type: "Dynamically typed" }
]);
